# ui-elements

RULE: Assign UI elements to a global variable and include them as the last expression of a cell to display them.
RULE: Never access a UI element's `.value` in the same cell where it is defined — the value is only available in downstream cells.
RULE: UI element values are accessed via the `.value` attribute in downstream cells.
```python
@app.cell
def _(df, mo):
    slider = mo.ui.slider.from_series(df["year"], label="Year")
    slider                             # display the slider
    return (slider,)

@app.cell
def _(df, mo, slider):
    filtered = df.filter(pl.col("year") == slider.value)  # access .value here
    mo.ui.table(filtered)
    return (filtered,)
```

**Available UI elements:**
- `mo.ui.slider(start, stop)` — numeric slider
- `mo.ui.dropdown(options)` — dropdown selector
- `mo.ui.checkbox(label)` — checkbox
- `mo.ui.text(label)` — text input
- `mo.ui.text_area(label)` — multi-line text input
- `mo.ui.date()` — date picker
- `mo.ui.table(data)` — interactive table with selection
- `mo.ui.dataframe(df)` — interactive dataframe transformer
- `mo.ui.altair_chart(chart)` — reactive altair chart
- `mo.ui.matplotlib(ax)` — reactive matplotlib plot
- `mo.ui.plotly(fig)` — reactive plotly chart
- `mo.ui.run_button(label)` — button that triggers downstream cells

