# expensive-cells

RULE: Use `@mo.cache` to cache the result of an expensive cell function — the result is reused on re-run if inputs have not changed.
RULE: Use `mo.persistent_cache` to cache variables to disk across sessions.
RULE: Use `mo.stop(condition, mo.md("message"))` to conditionally halt execution of a cell and all downstream cells.
```python
@app.cell
@mo.cache
def _(pl):
    df = pl.read_parquet("data/raw/large_file.parquet")  # cached after first run
    return (df,)
```

---

# notebook-conventions

RULE: One notebook, one question — do not let a notebook grow to answer multiple unrelated questions.
RULE: All reusable logic belongs in `src/{{ package_name }}` — notebooks call `src/` functions, they do not reimplement them.
RULE: Keep data loading cells isolated at the top of the notebook.
RULE: Use descriptive cell function names instead of `_` when the cell has a clear purpose — e.g. `def load_raw_data_(pl):` — this makes the dependency graph readable.
RULE: Use `hide_code=True` on `@app.cell` for cells whose output is the point and whose code is implementation detail: `@app.cell(hide_code=True)`.
RULE: Exploratory notebooks can be rough — the standard rises when a notebook becomes a deliverable or is run as an app.
